::: {.analysis-card}

Together, these visualizations suggest that cleanup efficiency is not explained by GDP or volunteer count alone. The regional tables show that Africa has the highest average cleanup efficiency, even though it has the lowest average and median GDP per capita among the regions shown. In contrast, Oceania has the highest average GDP per capita but the lowest average cleanup efficiency. This weakens the idea that higher GDP automatically leads to better cleanup outcomes.

The volunteer scatterplot also does not show a clear positive relationship between GDP per capita and total volunteers. Most countries are clustered at relatively low volunteer totals across a wide range of GDP values, while a few countries appear as high-volunteer outliers. This suggests that volunteer participation may depend on factors beyond national income, such as cleanup organization, event availability, country size, local environmental campaigns, or reporting differences.

Overall, the visual evidence suggests that cleanup efficiency varies strongly by region, but the relationship between GDP, volunteer count, and cleanup efficiency is not straightforward. Higher economic resources may help, but they do not guarantee higher cleanup efficiency in this dataset.

:::

::: {.analysis-card}

# So, what does this all mean?

This analysis shows that GDP status may relate to the dominant types of plastic waste found across countries, but the relationship is not simple or fully consistent. The regional cleanup results suggest that higher GDP and higher volunteer counts do not automatically lead to better cleanup efficiency, since some lower-GDP regions show stronger efficiency than higher-GDP regions. Overall, the findings point to cleanup outcomes being shaped by multiple factors beyond economic resources alone, including regional participation, organization, reporting, and local cleanup conditions.

:::